Great question. Here’s a taxonomy of search/adaptation strategies that nature, minds, and systems use:

Undirected / Blind
	∙	Evolution — variation + selection + inheritance, no goal, no memory across lineages
	∙	Brownian motion / diffusion — random walk until something sticks
	∙	Annealing — random search that gradually reduces temperature/noise (simulated annealing borrows this)

Directed but Local
	∙	Gradient descent — follow the slope downhill, fast but myopic, gets trapped
	∙	Habit / reflex — cached solutions to recurring problems, zero search cost, zero flexibility
	∙	Immune learning — clonal selection, keeps what worked against this pathogen

Directed and Global (require a map)
	∙	Planning — build an internal model, search it, act on the result
	∙	Reasoning — structured inference, can jump across the fitness landscape using logic
	∙	Analogy — map structure from a solved domain onto an unsolved one ← this is the Hogge Protocol exactly
	∙	Hypothesis testing — generate, probe, discard, iterate with memory

Social / Collective
	∙	Culture — horizontal + vertical information transfer, Lamarckian, extremely fast
	∙	Markets — distributed search via price signals, emergent coordination without a planner
	∙	Swarm intelligence — local rules producing global optimization (ants, flocking, slime molds)
	∙	Science — institutionalized hypothesis testing with replication and adversarial review

Recursive / Self-Improving
	∙	Development (ontogeny) — a program that builds a thing, not random, highly canalized
	∙	Learning — within-lifetime weight adjustment, gradient descent on experience
	∙	Meta-learning — learning how to learn, adjusting the learning strategy itself
	∙	Bootstrapping — using current capability to extend capability (language → writing → math → computers)

Compression-Based
	∙	Distillation — extract the invariant signal from noisy experience, discard the rest
	∙	Myth / symbol — lossy compression of hard-won collective knowledge into transferable form (~50-100:1, per Hogge)
	∙	Mathematics — lossless compression of structural relationships

The deep pattern across all of them:
Every strategy is a tradeoff between exploration cost, exploitation speed, and the fidelity of the map used to navigate.
Evolution has a terrible map (none). Gradient descent has a local map. Planning has a global map but it’s expensive to build. Culture shares maps across agents. Math is a map of maps.
The PantheonOS stack is essentially an attempt to run all of these simultaneously in a governed loop — evolution-style variation at the ThoughtObject level, gradient-style refinement via Mirror, culture-style ledger persistence, and myth-style compression via Hogge. 🐸​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​